column4: For “A Blockchain‐Based Micro Economy Platform for Distributed Infrastructure Initiatives,” the evaluation method appears to use a structured approach based on an “Evaluation Method List” that is embedded in a broader evaluation framework typical for software architecture studies. In contrast, “Integrating Statistical Response Time Models in Architectural Performance Models” uses an evaluation approach that specifically integrates quantitative statistical response time models into architectural performance models, emphasizing simulation and quantitative performance metrics. In short, while the blockchain-based work builds its evaluation on a standardized list of evaluation criteria and considerations (typical of qualitative-to-quantitative criteria in distributed systems), the statistical model–based work directly models and tests performance parameters via statistical analysis.

column112: Which publications have the evaluation sub-property [evaluation sub-property name] ranked by the publication year?

column4:
Based on the provided evidence, the following papers have evaluation chains reaching the property “Reliability”:
1. Empirical Insights into the Evolving Role of Architects in Decision-Making in an Agile Context (publication year: 2018)
2. Microservice Ambients: An Architectural Meta-Modelling Approach for Microservice Granularity (publication year: not specified)
3. A Platform Architecture for Multi-Tenant Blockchain-Based Systems (publication year: not specified)
4. Dynamic Updates of Virtual PLCs Deployed as Kubernetes Microservices (publication year: not specified)
5. Experiments in Curation: Towards Machine-Assisted Construction of Software Architecture Knowledge Bases (publication year: not specified)

Since only one paper has an explicit publication year, we rank it first, and list the remaining papers (which are linked via evidence to an evaluation of “Reliability”) collectively in an undetermined order.

column103: Which papers use the evaluation method Questionnaire but indicate that no input data was used?
column104: The papers that use the evaluation method Questionnaire but do not have any input data available are: 'Architectural Assumptions and Their Management in Industry – An Exploratory Study' and 'Determining Microservice Boundaries: A Case Study Using Static and Dynamic Software Analysis'. Both papers indicate that there is no input data available for their respective studies.

column4:
Based on the available evidence, the evaluation methods applied by Uwe Zdun in papers addressing Architecture Decision Making include approaches documented under the “Evaluation Method List.” In particular, Uwe Zdun’s publications in this research area report using customized evaluation methods such as:
 • A qualitative multi‐method study approach (as evidenced by the study titled “Architectural Design Decisions for Systems Supporting Model-Based Analysis of Runtime Events: A Qualitative Multi-method Study”)
 • An evaluation approach that employs optimal approximations on Apache Hadoop checkpoint techniques (as evidenced by the publication “Employment of Optimal Approximations on Apache Hadoop Checkpoint Technique for Performance Improvements”)
Overall, Uwe Zdun’s contributions rely on applying structured evaluation methods that are part of the “Evaluation Method List” framework, covering both qualitative and quantitative (performance‐related) assessments.

column112: From [year 1] to [year 2], how frequently per year have the research objects of papers been evaluated with the evaluation method with the name [Content Data: evaluation method name]?

column4: Between 2019 and 2021, there are three instances where research objects evaluated with Grounded Theory appear. One evaluation instance is linked to a publication from 2019 (“An Exploratory Study of Naturalistic Decision Making in Complex Software Architecture Environments”), one to a 2020 publication (“Data Stream Operations as First-Class Entities in Component-Based Performance Models”), and one to a 2021 publication (“Identifying Domain-Based Cyclic Dependencies in Microservice APIs Using Source Code Detectors”). In short, one evaluation instance per year is observed in the provided context.
